{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9013f31e-1560-43e0-9492-2f3266c473d7","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a built-in .NET MAUI `ContentPage` property — that's likely why it's having no effect. Here's what you actually need:\n\n### iOS — disable safe area padding\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n### Android — enable edge-to-edge\nIn `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n    Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n}\n```\n\n### XAML\n```xml\n<ContentPage ...\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n    Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           VerticalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` is the real iOS property — it lets content extend behind the notch/home indicator.\n- On Android, `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false)` tells the system your app will handle insets itself. Transparent bars let the image show through.\n- If your page is in a `Shell`, also set `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` to remove the navigation bar chrome.\n- .NET 10 targeting Android 15 (API 35) enforces edge-to-edge by default, but MAUI's layout system still respects insets unless you configure the window as shown above.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"802cd90a-3b4c-48e5-8975-8ef18e49a903","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"No relevant content in the repository. Let me answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on a `ContentPage` tells the page not to automatically pad content away from safe areas. However, starting with newer versions of .NET MAUI (and especially relevant for .NET 10), there are additional considerations:\n\n1. **Android**: Starting with Android 15 (API 35), apps are edge-to-edge by default. But for older targets, you may need to opt in. In .NET MAUI, the status bar and navigation bar may still cause the content to be inset.\n\n\n2. **iOS**: The safe area insets are applied by default, and `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` should help, but you also need to make sure the page content actually extends behind the bars. The real issue is that `SafeAreaEdges` controls automatic padding on the page itself, but individual views might also need `IgnoreSafeArea` set, or there could be platform-specific configuration needed to truly go edge-to-edge.\n\nFor .NET MAUI / .NET 10, on iOS setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` should let content go behind the status bar and home indicator, while on Android you need platform-specific setup like making the status bar and navigation bar transparent and using the edge-to-edge APIs—though .NET 10 with Android 15+ enforces this by default, older versions require opting in.\n\nIf the user set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` but still sees padding, the culprit is likely a `Shell` or `NavigationPage` wrapper adding its own chrome, or on Android the platform-specific configuration isn't properly applied. In .NET MAUI, the iOS approach uses `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` to disable safe area padding, but Android's edge-to-edge handling is more complex—newer versions like Android 15 enforce it by default, though the MAUI layout system might still add padding that requires platform-specific code or `WindowInsets` handling to fully remove. Setting up Android edge-to-edge display...","outputTokens":1957,"requestId":"043E:2086DF:13B7471:1610EED:6A027C6D"},"id":"2f1652bf-9184-4aa9-a4fa-3a147cb11b6e","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:04:19.751Z","parentId":"32640adc-9c47-4ad3-bc